description: 15th Annual Art History Graduate Student Symposium Join us for a full-day symposium exploring the power of art in times of crisis. This year’s theme, Artivism: Art History and Heritage in Global Conflict, brings together graduate students from across the globe to examine how art and heritage respond to, resist, and reflect conflict. Topics range from protest art and cultural resilience to the destruction of heritage sites and censorship. We are excited to host Dr. Elisabeth Friedman (Illinois State University) as our keynote speaker, presenting “Photography as Archive: The Art of Dor Guez,” a powerful exploration of contemporary art, memory, and resistance. All are welcome; students, faculty, and community members across departments. Food and refreshments will be served throughout the day, and attendees are welcome to join us either in person or via Zoom.
name: Artivism: Art History and Heritage in Global Conflict

description: This panel is ideal for students and professionals interested in:  Politics Law (Law School) Public Service Public Policy Labor studies  Journalism Public Relations Marketing Government Relations Human Resources  Gender Studies  Join us on Wednesday, April 2nd, 2025, from 6:00–7:30 PM at the Douglass Student Center Lounge for an inspiring and empowering event featuring five trailblazing women in politics. This panel promises a dynamic conversation about their journeys, challenges, and triumphs in navigating politics, public service, and advocacy. Meet Our Esteemed Speakers:  Dr. Patricia Campos Medina: A labor activist and educator, Dr. Medina holds leadership roles, including Executive Director of the Worker Institute at Cornell University. With an extensive background in trade relations and public policy, Dr. Medina is currently campaigning for the U.S. Senate. Deirdre Malone: The 15th president of the National Women’s Political Caucus, Deirdre Malone has made history as the first African American woman to chair the Shelby County Commission and run for Shelby County mayor. She is also the founder and CEO of The Carter Malone Group. Allison Chris Myers: Chairwoman and CEO of the New Jersey Civil Service Commission, Allison Chris Myers brings expertise in administrative law, human resources, and regulatory affairs. She has a rich academic background from Rutgers School of Law. Dr. Sadaf Jaffer: Former mayor of Montgomery Township and a prominent scholar, Dr. Jaffer is the first South Asian American woman to serve as mayor in New Jersey and the first Muslim woman mayor in the U.S. She is also an Associate Research Scholar at Princeton University. Ginger Gold Schnitzer: Director of Education and Strategic Initiatives at the Eagleton Institute of Politics, Ginger Schnitzer has a deep background in political education and government relations, with a strong history of leadership in local government and advocacy. Eileen Kean: government affairs attorney and president of Komjathy & Kean, LLC, specializing in lobbying for national companies. She attended Seton Hall Law School, later joining Thomas Kean Associates to focus on government affairs. She has served as CEO of the Independent Insurance Agents of New Jersey and president of the Deal School Board of Education.She was also Director of Government Affairs for the Medical Society of New Jersey.Eileen is a Commissioner of the Monmouth County Board of Elections, appointed by Governors Christie and Murphy. She also serves on the NJ State Board of Pharmacy and is a trustee of the Drumthwacket Foundation. She actively participates in national organizations such as the Governors Associations and the National Conference of State Legislators.  This event is a unique opportunity to engage with these remarkable women who have reshaped the political landscape and have made significant strides in advocating for gender, racial, and economic justice. Dress Code: Business casual RSVP: Please fill out the Google Sheet to secure your spot for the panel and free food! Don’t miss out on this incredible networking and learning opportunity!
name: RUWPC: Women in Politics Panel– An Evening of Empowerment and Insight

description: Synaptic dysfunction and dendritic spine abnormalities often underlie the cognitive symptoms of neurodevelopmental disorders. Within the dendritic spine, synaptic proteins such as receptors, signaling molecules, and scaffolding proteins are organized into sub-compartments called nanomodules. Previous studies have found that the number of nanomodules increases in proportion to synaptic strength and spine size, with immature spines having fewer nanomodules compared to mature spines. Nevertheless, the molecular players driving the formation of nanomodules in the synapse are not fully characterized. The scaffolding protein Partitioning Defective 3 (Par3) is known to promote subcellular compartmentalization. Furthermore, recent work in our lab has found that loss of Par3 in mice results in an increased pool of immature dendritic spines. Therefore, we hypothesize that Par3 may promote dendritic spine maturation and stability by driving the formation of nanomodules within the postsynaptic density. Unexpectedly, I recently discovered that Par3 colocalizes and interacts with PSD95, a key postsynaptic scaffolding protein. Moreover, I have narrowed this interaction down to be between the C-terminal 4N2 domain of Par3 and the N-terminus of PSD95. Currently, I am working to further characterize the Par3-PSD95 interaction by exploring whether this interaction relies on phase separation, a common mechanism for subcellular compartmentalization of proteins. Additionally, I am using super-resolution microscopy to examine the interaction between these two proteins in neurons and how synaptic activity affects the potential role of Par3 in regulating nanomodule formation at the synapse.
name: NeuroConnections Seminar - Hanna Caiola

description: A cup of Coffee & A Fresh Start: What if a simple cup of coffee could spark a conversation that changes your life? Join us for a free cup of coffee, enjoy sweet treats, and explore the support and community available through the Rutgers Alcohol & Other Drug Assistance Program (ADAP). Take a moment to unwind at our sensory station, designed to help you relax and reset. Whether you're in recovery, supporting a friend, or just curious about wellness resources, this is a judgment-free zone where conversations can lead to connections—and maybe even transformation.
location: Bishop Beach ( Across the Street From Panera)
name: Mental Health Awareness Week 2025: Coffee and Conversation

description: Join us for an interactive wellness event where you can enjoy free ice cream while learning about campus resources! Here’s how it works:   Check-In: Students will receive a punch card upon arrival.   Engage & Explore: Visit at least three activity stations to complete your punch card. Each station offers:   -A small interactive activity.   -Information about a campus resource.   -A chance to ask questions or participate in fun institutional trivia.   Get Your Ticket: Once you’ve completed three stations, you’ll earn a ticket for the ice cream truck!   This event is open to 200 participants on a first-come, first-served basis. Don’t miss this opportunity to connect, learn, and treat yourself!
name: Mental Health Awareness Week 2025: I- Scream for ICE CREAM

description: CAMPFIRE: 🌙 Gather around the fire for a Reflection Circle, sharing thoughts and experiences from the week. 📝 Burn & Release – Write down something that no longer serves you and release it into the fire as a symbolic act of letting go. 🍫 S’mores & Music – Enjoy sweet treats and soothing tunes to end the week on a positive note.   Take this time to honor your journey, embrace new beginnings, and carry forward the tools and insights gained throughout the week.
location: Bishop Beach ( Across the Street From Panera)
name: Mental Health Awareness Week 2025: Campfire & Smores

description: The annual Rites of Passage Ceremony is a pre-commencement celebration to honor Black and Latinx/e-identified students who through resolute persistence have successfully completed an undergraduate or graduate degree at Rutgers University—New Brunswick. The event recognizes their accomplishments, hard work, and dedication, while simultaneously acknowledging the accomplishments of our student’s families and networks of support. Distinguished speakers, student awards, performances, and the incorporation of African culture and traditions—specifically the culminating Kente Stole presentation—all add to the vibrancy of this celebratory day. Participation in the Rites of Passage Ceremony is open to all Black and Latinx-identified Rutgers University–New Brunswick Undergraduate and Graduate students who have earned their degrees between January 2025 and August 2025. To participate, students must register by Friday, May 2nd, 2025 through the getINVOLVED portal. Only students registered by the deadline will be guaranteed Rites of Passage graduate perks and able to ensure you have tickets for guests.  All graduates are required to wear their academic regalia, which can be purchased from the Barnes and Noble Rutgers University Bookstore on Somerset Street. There is no cost to participate in Rites of Passage for graduates or guests. All graduates who register will receive the following:-1 Free Kente Cloth Stole-7 guest tickets-Access to reception - Digital Invitation Downloads  If you have specific questions about your registration or the ceremony, please email rop@echo.rutgers.edu. Please note that all graduates need to be checked-in between 2:30-3:30pm. The graduation will start promptly at 4:00pm.  Visit the Rites of Passage website for more information!
name: 33rd Annual Rites of Passage Ceremony Registration
organizationNames: Center for Latino Arts and Culture
Paul Robeson Cultural Center
